CaseSummary.Summary: Vehicle one (V1 - case vehicle), a 2000 GMC Sonoma, 3-door extended cab pickup truck was traveling north in the left northbound lane of a four-lane, two-way road (two lanes northbound, two lanes southbound). Vehicle two (V2), a 2001 Buick Regal, 4-door sedan was traveling south in the right southbound lane of the same road. It was dark and sleeting and the bituminous road surface was icy. The driver of V1 lost control on the icy surface and his vehicle began a counterclockwise rotation as it crossed the centerline of the road. The driver of V2 was unable to avoid V1 and the front of V2 struck the right side of V1 in a T-type configuration. Both vehicles were towed due to disabling vehicle damage. The 26-year-old female driver of V2 was transported to a local hospital and hospitalized with unknown injuries. The 23-year-old male driver of V1 (case occupant) was using the available three-point seat belt but no air bags deployed. He was transported via ground ambulance to a local hospital and later transferred to a regional level-one trauma center.

CirenCaseForm.InjuryAnalysis:
The case occupant is the 178 cm, 113 kg (5 ft 10 in, 250 lb), 23-year-old male driver of a 2000 GMC Sonoma, 3-door extended cab pickup who lost control on an icy road, rotated counterclockwise and was struck in the right-side by the front of a 2001 Buick Regal, 4-door sedan in a T-type configuration. The impact was classified as severe and the Win SMASH reconstruction program calcualted a delta-v of 57 kmph (35 mph) which appeared to be consistent with the observed vehicle damage. The case occupant was using the available three-point seat belt but no air bags deployed.
On impact, he moved to his right, relative to the vehicle interior, in response to the 3 o'clock direction of force. He sustained two right posterior rib fractures (#11 and 12, with #11 being displaced) with hemothorax, bilateral lung contusions, a liver laceration, five right-sided lumbar transverse process fractures, a retroperitoneal hematoma, a spleen laceration, and a right kidney contusion from contact with the center armrest/intruding right door. Extensive right-sided intrusions likely played a contributing factor in the severity of these injuries. He also sustained a right sacral fracture probably from contact with the lap belt. He also sustained a right medial malleolus fracture via foot inversion from contact with the toepan/floor.
